{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6e919924-ddde-43a2-aa27-b0b689b607a5","content":"## What's happening\n\n**.NET 11 raised the minimum x86-64 microarchitecture level**, likely from **x86-64-v2** (required since .NET 10 on Linux) to **x86-64-v3**. The runtime checks CPU feature flags at startup and refuses to run if the baseline isn't met.\n\n### The x86-64 microarchitecture levels\n\n| Level | Key additions | Earliest CPUs | Year |\n|-------|--------------|---------------|------|\n| **v1** | SSE, SSE2 (original x86-64) | AMD K8 / Intel Prescott | ~2003 |\n| **v2** | SSE4.2, POPCNT, SSSE3, CMPXCHG16B | Intel Nehalem | ~2009 |\n| **v3** | **AVX2**, FMA, BMI1/2, LZCNT, MOVBE | Intel Haswell | **~2013** |\n| **v4** | AVX-512 | Intel Skylake-X | ~2017 |\n\n### Why your 2012 node fails\n\nYour 2012-era hardware is likely **Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge**. These CPUs support **v2** (SSE4.2, POPCNT ✓) but **not v3** — they have AVX but lack **AVX2, FMA, and BMI1/2**, which arrived with Haswell in 2013.\n\n- **.NET 10** required v2 → 2012 hardware worked ✓\n- **.NET 11** requires v3 → 2012 hardware fails ✗\n\n### Why your other targets are unaffected\n\n- **Windows Arm64 (SQ1):** Arm has its own baseline (Armv8.0+). SQ1 is Armv8-compliant. x86-64 levels don't apply.\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Cortex-A72):** Also Armv8-A. Same — unaffected by x86-64 baseline changes.\n\n### Options\n\n1. **Retire the pre-Haswell hardware** — the simplest path; these CPUs are 13+ years old.\n2. **Build a custom runtime** with a lower baseline by setting `DOTNET_EnableSSE41=0`-style flags or building the runtime from source targeting v2, though this is unsupported.\n3. **Stay on .NET 10 LTS** for workloads that must run on that hardware while migrating others to .NET 11.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9e27fa3b-2f88-4143-b5ae-4b2a1135bf17","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .